  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing the Requirements**\n\nI\'ve just finished reviewing the `gemini-api` skill. Now, I\'m focusing on understanding the user\'s ultimate goal: to build a precise pixel-level image isolation engine. I\'m cross-referencing this goal against the methodologies outlined in the system guidelines to begin developing a plan.\n\n\n**Refining the Constraints**\n\nI\'ve zeroed in on the constraints and core requirements. The `metadata.json` will be updated to reflect the project scope, and the `majorCapabilities` will be set accordingly. I\'m focusing on the explicit user requests \342\200\223 segmentation, chroma key, and Python masking. The main challenge now is figuring out how to run Python code within the Node sandbox. I need to confirm the availability of `shell_exec` and its implementation to execute commands for this, because this may be where this integration lives.\n\n\n**Investigating Execution Methods**\n\nI am now focusing on how to execute the Python script the user requires for image processing. Although `shell_exec` is available, its permitted commands are limited to grep, npx, and gradle. I must rethink how I\'ll run the OpenCV/PIL script to generate the alpha mask. Currently, the limitations on `shell_exec` are blocking the execution of arbitrary Python scripts directly. I need to find another way to handle this essential part of the workflow.\n\n\n**Exploring Gemini Integration Options**\n\nI\'m now investigating how the Gemini API can fit into this pipeline, considering the inability to directly execute a Python script. There\'s a breakthrough! I can use Gemini 2.5 Flash Image to generate or edit images, possibly including green screen transforms or preliminary mask identification. Alternatively, I can use Gemini 3.5 or 3.1 Pro for more advanced image analysis. Further, I can implement a purely front-end solution using canvas.\n\n\n**Developing the Frontend Approach**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in the front-end approach! I\'ve realized that using standard HTML5 Canvas with ImageData provides direct, precise pixel-level analysis for chroma-keying, alpha mask generation, and morphological tweaks. I\'m imagining interactive pixel adjustments for thresholding, erosion/dilation, and edge refinement, offering users instant visual feedback. I\'m exploring an API route that can process the image using standard canvas, or a similar alternative. The user will be given a visualizer to preview their code. This is very exciting!\n\n\n**Designing the Interface**\n\nI am now visualizing the user experience, focusing on a professional dashboard theme. It\'ll be charcoal and deep slate. First, the user uploads an image, which Gemini 3.5 Flash analyzes on the backend for subject detection and metadata. Then, the user will interact with a pixel-level green screen editor to transform and isolate the subject. This includes an interactive canvas-based pencil or brush.\n\n\n**Implementing Python Code Preview**\n\nI\'m now integrating automated subject isolation features, leveraging color thresholding and contour tracing, with adjustable background tolerance sliders. The system defaults to keying out the `#00FF00` green screen, but supports any background color. Crucially, I\'ll generate and display the precise Python script using OpenCV and PIL, showing the HSV conversion, chroma keying, alpha mask creation, morphological operations, and the saving process. I\'ll include an option to \"Simulate Execution\" to present a log. I am unsure if I can run the Python script on the server itself, so I\'m investigating simulating the exact code on the canvas, with the log.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 9
      nanos: 571212974
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
